a plant which, as we shall hereafter see, feeds on decayed animal matter. As urea i
s one of the last products of the chemical changes going on in the living body, it seems fitted to represent the early stages of the decay of the dead body. I was also led to try urea from a curious little fact mentioned by Prof. Cohn, namely that when ra
ther large crustaceans are caught between the closing lobes, they are pressed so hard whilst making their escape that they often void their sausage\_
